# The nervous system CNS & PNS 


**Important concepts and terms:**
Distinguish between central and peripheral nervous system.


**The central nervous system CNS:** 
- The central nervous system consists of the brain and spinal cord. 
- The CNS and PNS work together and are connected to each other.
- The CNS performs information processsing and integration. It revies information, stores the information as memories and creates the appropriate motor reesponse. 
- The CNS generates motor output. Meaning that nerve signals from the CNS go by way of the PNS to targeted muscle, glands and organs. 

**The peripheral nervous system PNS:**
- The peripheral nervous system consits of nerves, which lie outside of the CNS.
- External or internal stimuli generate nerve signals that travel by way ofthe PNS to the CNS. 
- The PNS connects the CNS to limbs and organs and serves as a relay between CNS and the rest of the body. 

![N1 CVS and PNS Reddest.png](data:image/png;base64,)

**Afferent nerves/neurons:**
- Carry sensory information from receptors inside the skin/other organs (PNS) to the CNS
- Cell bodies arelocated outside the spinal cord 
- Also called sensory neurons

**Efferent nerves/neurons:** 
- Carry motor information from brain (CNS) to the PNS. 
- Cell bodies are located in the spinal cord.
- Also called motor neurons.
